\begin_layout Subsection
State equations of a CTRNN unit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Canonical state equations of a CTRNN's neuron in a network of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 elements are 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BeerGallagher1992"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DiPaolo2000"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{i}\dot{y_{i}}=-y_{i}+\sum_{j=1}^{N}w_{ji}z_{j}+I_{i}\label{eq:CTRNN-unit-general-eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z_{j}=\frac{1}{1+e^{b_{j}-y_{j}}}\label{eq:CTRNN-unit-logistic-eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the time constant (
\begin_inset Formula $=RC$
\end_inset

 in the equivalent circuit) that allows for temporal summation of the incoming
 input, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

represents the cell potential of neuron 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, or the 
\emph on
value
\emph default
 of the neuron, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{ji}$
\end_inset

 is the weight of the connection from neuron 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 to neuron 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the incoming input, which is set to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 for all non input neurons.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 function is the ordinary sigmoid function that converts the potential of
 the neuron into a value in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 as a function of the neuron's potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, and the neuron's bias, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The bias term is the parameter in the neuron's state equation that allows
 for spatial summation of inputs.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This equation was originally proposes by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hop84a"

\end_inset

, on the basis of an analogy between neural networks and 
\begin_inset Formula $RC$
\end_inset

 electronic circuits, and expressed in terms of resistance, capacitance,
 and voltage potential, input current, (
\begin_inset Formula $R,C,V,I$
\end_inset

) for a neuron 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as: 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}\dot{u_{i}}=-\frac{u_{i}}{R_{i}}+\sum_{j}T_{ij}V_{j}+I_{i}$
\end_inset

, where the summative term represents the weighted inputs to neuron 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, the second term represents transmembrane resistance, and the final term,
 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}$
\end_inset

, is the externally applied input to the neuron.
 Normalizing with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}=R_{i}C_{i}$
\end_inset

 leads to eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:CTRNN-unit-general-eq"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ":30"
key "Beer1990"

\end_inset

.
 Although this formulation has now become canonical in the evolutionary
 robotics literature, Beer's original formulas were more complex and included
 additional parameters describing the intrinsic currents generated within
 a neuron as well as the leak currents flowing out of it (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ":51"
key "Beer1990"

\end_inset

).
 As these complications were ignored by the subsequent literature, we will
 not discuss them here, although it should not be exceedingly difficult
 to incorporate them in the model, especially because Beer, following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hop84a"

\end_inset

, models biological neurons on the basis of electronic circuits.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
State equation of a Homeostat unit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ashby describes the behavior of the 4-unit Homeostat as follows in 
\emph on
Design of a Brain
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after " p. 247, 19/12"
key "Ashby1960"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dx_{i}}{dt}=\dot{x_{i}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}(m\dot{x})=-k\dot{x_{i}}+l(p-q)(a_{i1}x_{1}+...+a_{i4}x_{4})\label{eq:Ashby-unit-eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 unit's needle's angle of deviation, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is its moment of inertia, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are the potentials at the opposite ends of the fluid-filled trough, 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 represents the frictional forces acting on the needle's movement, and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

depends on the valve,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 i.e.
 it is a gain parameter.
 Rewriting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Ashby-unit-eq"

\end_inset

 in notation closer to CTRNN's would give us, for a Homeostat of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 units:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m\ddot{x}_{i}=-k\dot{x}_{i}+l(p-q)\sum_{j=1}^{N}a_{ij}x_{j}\label{eq:Unit-CTRNN-not}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Ashby's device, the gain parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, and the difference in potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $p-q$
\end_inset

, are the same for all units,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Or so it seems from Ashby's discussions of his device in all published descripti
ons he gave.
 At any rate, they are never mentioned in the concrete experiments carried
 out with the homeostat.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 thus allowing to slightly simplify the equation by assuming a constant
 gain factor 
\begin_inset Formula $g=l(p-q)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m\ddot{x}_{i}=-k\dot{x}_{i}+g\sum a_{ij}x_{j}\label{eq:Unit-CTRNN-not-with-constant}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
My implementation substantially follows equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Unit-CTRNN-not"

\end_inset

, with the difference that it does 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
assume 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 to be the same across all units.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a slightly different take on the issue: notice that the homeostat's
 units cold also be seen as oscillators.
 Start with a single unit.
 If we provide a negative self-connection, and assume no frictional forces
 (i.e.
 the viscosity of the fluid in the trough is 0), then 
\begin_inset Formula $-k\dot{x}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Unit-CTRNN-not-with-constant"

\end_inset

 becomes 0 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\sum a_{ij}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 becomes simply 
\begin_inset Formula $-ga_{jj}x$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ii}$
\end_inset

being the weight of the self-connection.
 Putting 
\begin_inset Formula $ga_{ii=}k$
\end_inset

, the unit's behavior is described by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\ddot{x}=-kx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is the canonical equation for a harmonic oscillator.
 If we add a viscosity factor 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 due to the trough's fluid and assume it proportional to velocity, we obtain
 the canonical equation for a damped oscillator: 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ddot{x}=-v\dot{x}-kx$
\end_inset

 .
 Thus, the basic building block of a Homeostat is a damped harmonic oscillator.
 And a Homeostat (leaving uniselectors' action aside) is simply a collection
 of variously coupled harmonic oscillators.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, in a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real-world
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 translation of the homeostat we can assume that the real world input the
 unit are connected to are not self-regulating, i.e.
 they are not (damped) harmonic oscillators.
 It follows that a 
\emph on
single
\emph default
 negatively self-connected unit connected to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 environment is equivalent to a driven harmonic oscillator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\ddot{x}=-v\dot{x}-kx+aF(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $F(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 are, respectively, the input the unit is receiving from the environment
 and the weight it assigns to that input.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real world
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Homeostat (or its equivalent homeostat simulation, if possible) is thus
 a collection of driven harmonic oscillators (uniselectors' actions aside).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparison between the two
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The comparison between
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:CTRNN-unit-general-eq"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Unit-CTRNN-not"

\end_inset

 can be carried out at three levels: the general shape of the description
 (the model), the terms involved, and the relation between a unit's value
 (i.e.
 potential and rotation angle, resp., for CTRNNs and Ashby) and a unit's
 output.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The mathematical model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is where we find the greatest difference between the two.
 Although the models are remarkably similar, the important difference is
 that the value 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (potential) of CTRNN unit is defined in terms of its 
\emph on
first
\emph default
 derivative, whereas the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 of a Ashbian unit is expressed in term of its 
\emph on
second 
\emph default
and first derivatives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mechanically interpreted in traditional notation: 
\begin_inset Formula $F=ma$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m\dot{v}=F$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\dot{s}$
\end_inset

, with the traditional abbreviations for mass, acceleration, velocity and
 displacement, where the force 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 acting on the object can be further decomposed in a reactive frictional
 force proportional to velocity plus the active forces acting on the object
 (assuming, that is, the simplest mathematical model of friction).
 Thus the unit is fundamentally modeled as a Newtonian object rotating on
 a friction-affected pivot, and the basic parameters affecting its value
 (angular position) are its mass (or moment of inertia) and the friction
 it exerts (assuming the difference in potential is a constant; otherwise
 it would have one additional parameter): 
\begin_inset Formula $m,k,(p-q)$
\end_inset

.
 If we try to interpret the CTRNN unit mechanically, for the sake of comparing
 it to the Homeostat, we see that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:CTRNN-unit-general-eq"

\end_inset

 can be read as the model of an 
\emph on
Aristotelian 
\emph default
object, that is, an object whose velocity is proportional to the forces
 it is subjected to.
 In other words, the CTRNN unit is normally at rest in absence of incoming
 forces (its biological equivalent, the real neuron having an appropriately
 called resting potential), whereas a Homeostat's unit in the same situation
 is in uniform motion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Not really sure about the preceding point.
 Here is a tentative but perhaps better discussion.
 Notice, however, that there is really no notion of inertial mass in Aristotelia
n physics, so the interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 as such is not quite correct.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem is that a straightforward 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Aristotelian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dynamical model would have velocity equal to force over mass (
\begin_inset Formula $F=mv$
\end_inset

 or, rather, 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\frac{F}{m}$
\end_inset

, in differential term: 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{ms}=F$
\end_inset

).
 Now, assuming, in the CTRNN case, that the forces are equal to the incoming
 inputs plus the externally applied current, and using 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 to represent the mechanical displacement, an Aristotelian model would give
 us the following equation: 
\begin_inset Formula $m\dot{y}=\sum_{j}w_{ij}y_{j}+I_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Comparing this equation with eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:CTRNN-unit-general-eq"

\end_inset

 makes the problem clear: we are missing a term.
 Namely, 
\begin_inset Formula $-y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 If we rewrite the equation according to its original formulation, though,
 namely as 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}\dot{y_{i}}=-\frac{y_{i}}{R_{i}}+\sum_{j}w_{ij}y_{j}+I_{i}$
\end_inset

, we can perhaps make some progress.
 Now this shows, interpreted mechanically, that the applied force has three
 components, one of which is proportional to displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and to a resistive factor 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and the other two are dependent on the directly applied forces.
 This is not quite the original Aristotelian dynamical model, which explains
 friction as proportional to mass (and therefore contained in the 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 term in the equation).
 Furthermore, having a resistive force proportional to displacement models,
 in mechanical terms, the resistance encountered when driving a stake through
 the ground, i.e.
 the resistance of an extended object entering a viscous fluid.
 I suppose what I am saying is that the electro-mechanical device that would
 (approximately) realize the CTRNN equation and be as close as possible
 to Ashby's contraption would be made up of 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
highly viscous 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wells
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (with and electric potential between surface and bottom) with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stakes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 being driven in and out of them.
 This part would implement the 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{y_{i}}{R_{i}}$
\end_inset

 term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
very heavy friction in the mechanism's joints, surface, etc.
 This would approximate the Aristotelian modeling of force being proportional
 to velocity and not to acceleration, and thus the 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}\dot{y_{i}}$
\end_inset

 component instead of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ddot{y_{i}}$
\end_inset

 component in Ashby's model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now the second big difference is that there is a linear function (in fact,
 the identity function) in Ashby's model, whereas there is a non-linear
 function, the logistic one, in CTRNN case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Go on from here
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main difference, of course, is that whereas Ashby's Units have an identity
 function from unit's value to output, CTRNN units have a sigmoid, hence
 a non-linear, though continuosly differentiable function.
 The reason behind the adoption of a sigmoid function nonlinear function
 is due to the wish to model the frequency coding properties of real neurons,
 since such a function converts, over a short time span, a neuron's value
 into a firing frequency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Say something on frequency coding for real value as the job being performed
 here by the sigmoid function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Notice, BTW, that Ashby is perfectly aware of the spiking, frequency coding
 capacities of the nervous system (obviously).
 See for instance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after " p. 57"
key "Ashby1947"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


