\begin_layout Subsubsection
Term to term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now for the equivalence with Ashby's Homeostat.
 Its units are electro-mechanical contraptions where the values of interest
 to the modeler are the physical properties of the constantly moving parts
 and the forces acting on them.
 The state of a unit is thus represented by the velocity of the needle,
 the mechanical force acting on it (that is, the torque produced by the
 magnets coiled around its pivot as a result of the incoming currents from
 the other units), the mass of the needle, and the resistance the needle
 encounters in its movement through the fluid-filled trough.
 A term by term equivalence is can perhaps be found by interpreting the
 capacitance 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 and resistance 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the CTRNN model as being, roughly, functional equivalent to, respectively,
 mass and friction in Ashby's model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Eliminate the stuff that follows this comment until the end of this subsubsectio
n
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In mechanical terms, since the decay constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 represents the neuron's resistance to a change of state, it is equivalent
 to needle's mass providing an inertial resistance against change of velocity.
 The bias term 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 represents a neuron's resistance against firing and is equivalent to the
 the frictional resistive forces acting against the needle's displacement.
 The weights of the incoming connections, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{ji},$
\end_inset

 are obviously equivalent to the various resistors values on the incoming
 currents, while the incoming current, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i},$
\end_inset

 is normally equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 unless the Homeostat's operator decides to manually manipulate one or more
 of the units (as in Ashby's various experiments), in which case it corresponds
 to the external force acting on the needle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since in the original Homeostat all units are constructionally identical,
 the only free parameters governing the evolution of the network are the
 weights 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{ij}$
\end_inset

 controlling the connections between the units.
 If, on the other hand, we consider the possibility of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Homeostat (rather easily realizable through a computer simulation, continuous
 or discrete), we should consider all the parameters in eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Unit-CTRNN-not"

\end_inset

 as being independent, as we can easily construct units with different masses,
 different viscosities, potentials, gains, etc.
 That means that the simulation (and training, perhaps via GA techniques)
 of a homeostat of 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 units would entail the determination of 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 parameters per unit (mass, viscosity, gain and potential) + 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 weights, totaling 
\begin_inset Formula $j(j+4)$
\end_inset

 networks parameters.
 This number is actually not very different from the CTRNN standard of 
